{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DwqkXBNniuKbTanHP8PpvG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the key questions framework.\n\n**Behavior 1**: Products marked as out-of-stock are excluded from the recommendation results regardless of their relevance score.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about filtering logic — checking if a product's stock status is checked before/after scoring. This could be a single function that filters based on a flag. The failure mode is: a product with high relevance score but out-of-stock status still appears in results. This is about the interaction between the filtering step and the ranking step. Could be a single unit test if the filter function is isolated, but the \"regardless of their relevance score\" suggests it's about the pipeline ordering — does filtering happen before or after ranking? This could be an Integration test if the failure only appears when the filtering and ranking modules interact.\n\n\n- If I can test the filter function in isolation by passing in a mix of in-stock and out-of-stock products with varying relevance scores and verifying only in-stock ones are returned, that's Unit level. No infrastructure or LLM dependencies needed, and it doesn't require multi-step orchestration.\n\n- For the second behavior, I'm looking at a similar pattern — the user preference filter reads blocked categories from settings and excludes matching products. This is also testable at Unit level with mocked user settings and test product data.\n\n**Behavior 3**: The recommendation algorithm ranks products matching recent browsing patterns higher than those without browsing signals. I need to determine if this requires real infrastructure or LLM dependencies — the core question is whether the ranking logic correctly weights browsing history in the algorithm.\n\nThe system description mentions the algorithm weighs purchase history, browsing patterns, and similar-user behavior, which could suggest ML-based ranking. But behavior 10 specifies that recommendations are deterministic for the same user state, so I'm treating this as a deterministic algorithm rather than one using a real neural network. That means Unit testing is appropriate — I can verify the ranking logic with stubbed user data and browsing history.\n\nFor pagination, I need to check two things: whether it returns the correct page offset and whether the ordering stays stable across repeated requests. The stability part is tricky — if the ranking module doesn't have a consistent sort key, pagination might return different orders on successive calls. But if I can test the ranking and pagination together in-process with controlled input data, I can verify this at the Integration level without needing to mock external dependencies. I'm settling on Integration for this one—the instability only manifests when ranking and pagination work together, so I need to run the full pipeline twice to catch it.\n\nFor the serendipity requirement, I can test it at the Unit level by mocking a user's browsing history and verifying that at least one recommended product comes from an unbrowsed category. Since the algorithm is deterministic, this should be straightforward to validate in isolation.\n\nFor cold-start handling, I'm thinking Unit level as well—I can stub out the popularity data and confirm that new users without history get recommendations based on that popularity signal rather than an empty result. The tricky part is whether popularity itself comes from a separate service, but with mocked data I can keep this at Unit.\n\nFor click tracking, the core question is whether recording the right product ID, position, and timestamp needs real infrastructure. Most of the logic—capturing those three fields correctly—can be tested at Unit or Integration with a fake database. The real risk is if the failure only surfaces when writing to actual persistent storage, but that's less likely than a logic bug in how the fields are assembled.\n\nI'm leaning toward Integration here. Mocking the storage layer would catch swapped fields or wrong values, but actually writing to a fake in-memory store gives me more confidence that the tracking and storage modules work together correctly. That feels like the right level of verification for this behavior.\n\nFor the performance test, mocking won't work — I need a realistic 100K product dataset to see if the algorithm actually scales. If the bottleneck is CPU-bound processing, an in-memory list might be enough, but if it's database queries, I'd need a real database. I'm going with System level since a 100K catalog typically implies database interactions.\n\nFor the purchase deprioritization behavior, I need to test the full flow: generate recommendations, record a purchase, then verify the purchased product drops in ranking on the next request. This is an integration test that spans multiple components.\n\nFor determinism, I'm checking whether the recommendation function produces identical output when called twice with the same input—that's a unit-level concern. But I need to clarify whether the algorithm depends on a real LLM or if it's deterministic by design. yes, calling the same function twice with identical inputs works if it's pure. But \"two separate requests\" implies the system might introduce non-determinism during independent request processing—like inconsistent random seeding or unpredictable set ordering—so I should test the full recommendation pipeline end-to-end at the Integration level. Let me lock in my final assessments: out-of-stock and user preference filtering are Unit-level, browsing pattern ranking is Unit, pagination stability requires Integration since it chains ranking with pagination, serendipity is Unit with controlled inputs, cold-start fallback is Unit, and click tracking needs Integration to verify the full flow.\n\nFor response time I need a System test against real scale, post-purchase deprioritization is Integration since purchase recording and recommendations share state, and determinism itself is Integration—calling the pipeline twice to confirm identical outputs. I'm second-guessing browsing pattern ranking though: if it's just a deterministic algorithm that weights recent browsing history, Unit is fine with stubbed data. But serendipity might actually be Integration if it's implemented as a post-processing step that interacts with other components rather than a standalone property. Now I'm assigning probability distributions across test levels for each scenario. For the filter logic tests, Unit testing dominates since they're isolated concerns—straightforward to verify with controlled inputs—though there's a small chance Integration testing becomes necessary if the filters interact with ranking. The preference filter follows the same pattern, and I'm moving through the remaining test cases to establish similar probability breakdowns. Now I'm looking at the weight distributions across different test types for the remaining metrics—click tracking completes with system and agentic components, then response time shows a strong emphasis on system-level testing, while post-purchase deprioritization and determinism both lean heavily toward integration testing.\n\nLet me verify each test actually matches its minimum required level—I'm checking that unit tests cover isolated filter and ranking functions, integration tests handle the full pipeline with pagination and click tracking, and the system test benchmarks the recommendation endpoint under load.\n\nFor the serendipity behavior, I'm keeping it at Integration since the diversity injection needs to be wired into the main ranking pipeline—it's not just a single function's output property. Similarly, determinism requires calling the full pipeline twice to verify the ranked lists are identical, which is inherently an integration-level concern.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9867,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9867},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"48272a95-853f-4bab-a8f7-1190d085ffcf","uuid":"33d94b13-b988-4484-b3ac-176d9b3d32d0"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DwqkXBNniuKbTanHP8PpvG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CiaiQ5Uf95BBRbf9v7qdCp","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Products marked as out-of-stock are excluded from the recommendation results regardless of their relevance score.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is that the filter doesn't apply (or applies after ranking, allowing high-score out-of-stock items through). This is testable in isolation by passing a product list with high-relevance out-of-stock items and verifying none appear in output. The 'regardless of relevance score' condition is a test-data concern, not a module-boundary concern. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed — fake product objects suffice. LLM-DEP: Deterministic filter. REJECTION-GATE: Would escalate to Integration only if the filter and ranker are separate modules that could be wired incorrectly, but the behavior's failure mode (an out-of-stock item appearing) is catchable by testing the filter function's output directly.","test_description":"Construct a mixed product list containing in-stock items with low relevance scores and out-of-stock items with artificially high relevance scores. Pass this list through the availability filter function. Assert that zero out-of-stock products appear in the output, regardless of their relevance score values.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.72,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The user preference filter correctly excludes product categories the user has explicitly blocked in their settings.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in the filter predicate itself — it either reads the wrong field from user settings or applies incorrect logic. A unit test can stub user settings (blocked categories = ['electronics', 'toys']) and pass a catalog containing items from those categories, verifying they are excluded. REAL-INFRA: No external dependencies needed. LLM-DEP: Deterministic. REJECTION-GATE: Would escalate to Integration only if settings are fetched at filter-call time from a separate module and the failure is in how settings are passed across that boundary. The behavior describes filter correctness, not settings-fetch correctness.","test_description":"Create a user profile object with two explicitly blocked categories and a product catalog with items spanning those blocked categories and several unblocked categories. Invoke the preference filter function. Assert that all products in blocked categories are absent from the output and all products in permitted categories are present.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.74,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The recommendation algorithm ranks products that match the user's recent browsing patterns higher than products with no browsing signal.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in the ranking algorithm's weight calculation — it either ignores the browsing signal or applies incorrect weights. This is testable by providing a controlled product set (some matching recent browses, some not) and a stub browsing history, then verifying rank ordering. REAL-INFRA: No real I/O needed. LLM-DEP: Behavior 10 asserts the system is deterministic, indicating a rule-based or weight-based algorithm rather than a non-deterministic ML model. REJECTION-GATE: Would escalate to Agentic if the ranker were a neural network with non-deterministic scoring, but determinism (behavior 10) disqualifies that path.","test_description":"Construct a product set where group A products match the stub user's recent browsing history and group B products have no browsing overlap. Call the ranking algorithm with this product set and browsing history. Assert that all group A products appear before all group B products in the ranked output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.63,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Pagination returns the correct page of results, with stable ordering — requesting page 2 twice returns identical results if the underlying data hasn't changed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The stability failure only manifests when the ranking module and pagination module are wired together and called twice — e.g., if the ranking uses a non-stable sort or a HashMap whose iteration order changes between calls. A unit test of the pagination slice function alone with a pre-sorted list cannot catch instability introduced by the upstream ranker. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed; an in-process wired pipeline catches the failure. LLM-DEP: No. REJECTION-GATE: Would lower to Unit if pagination were tested against a hardcoded pre-sorted list, but then we'd miss instability caused by the ranker re-sorting differently on successive calls.","test_description":"Wire the full recommendation pipeline (filter → rank → paginate) with a fixed user state and static catalog. Request page 2 (e.g., items 11–20) twice in succession without any intervening state changes. Assert that both responses return exactly the same product IDs in exactly the same order, and that page 2 contains the correct offset slice relative to the total ranked list.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.67,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The recommendation algorithm surfaces at least one product from a category the user hasn't browsed before (serendipity requirement), avoiding a filter bubble.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The serendipity requirement is most likely implemented as a post-processing module (diversity injector) wired after the main ranker. The failure — all results coming from browsed categories — only appears when the serendipity module is missing from or bypassed in the pipeline, not when any single function is wrong in isolation. REAL-INFRA: No real I/O needed; an in-process pipeline test with controlled catalog data catches this. LLM-DEP: Behavior 10 asserts determinism. REJECTION-GATE: Would lower to Unit only if serendipity is a single function whose output property can be verified without wiring to the ranker, but a standalone diversity function test would not catch the case where the diversity injector is never called in the pipeline.","test_description":"Build a user profile whose entire browsing history covers categories A and B only. Load a product catalog containing items exclusively from A and B, plus several items from category C (never browsed). Run the full recommendation pipeline. Assert that at least one product from category C appears in the recommendation output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A new user with no purchase or browsing history receives recommendations based on overall popularity rather than an empty result set.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in the cold-start branch of the recommendation function — it either returns empty or fails to fall back to the popularity signal. This branch is reachable by calling the recommendation function with an empty history object and stub popularity data. REAL-INFRA: No real I/O needed. LLM-DEP: No. REJECTION-GATE: Would escalate to Integration if popularity data is fetched from a separate module at call time and the failure is in that fetch-and-fallback wiring. But the behavior tests what the algorithm does with empty history, not how popularity data is fetched — stubbing popularity data is sufficient.","test_description":"Create a user object with empty purchase history and empty browsing history. Provide stub popularity-ranked product data. Call the recommendation algorithm. Assert that the returned list is non-empty, and that the order of returned products matches the descending popularity ranking of the stub data rather than any personalization signal.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.68,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"Click tracking records the correct product ID, position in the list, and timestamp for each recommendation the user interacts with.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure modes are field-mapping bugs — product_id and position swapped, timestamp not captured, wrong list position used. These only surface when the tracking module reads from the recommendation context and writes to the storage module. A pure unit test with a mock store only verifies call arguments, which passes even if the tracking module extracts the wrong field names. An in-process fake store lets us read back the written record and assert all three fields are correct. REAL-INFRA: An in-memory/fake store is sufficient — real DB writes are not needed to catch field-mapping bugs. LLM-DEP: No.","test_description":"Wire the click-tracking module with an in-memory event store. Simulate a recommendation response containing 5 products in a known order. Trigger a click event on the 3rd product. Read the written record from the in-memory store. Assert that the stored event contains the exact product_id of the 3rd item, position value 3, and a timestamp within a reasonable window of the simulated click time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"The response time for generating recommendations stays under 200ms for a catalog of 100,000 products.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: Performance at the 100K catalog scale depends on real execution: database index traversal, network round-trips, serialization costs, and OS scheduling — none of which are reproduced by in-process stubs. An in-memory list of 100K fake objects measures algorithmic complexity but hides the I/O-bound bottlenecks that dominate in production. The 200ms budget is a wall-clock SLA for a real HTTP response, not a CPU cycle budget. MOCK-HIDE: Any mock of the data layer will mask the real latency source, making the test always pass. REJECTION-GATE: Would lower to Integration only if the catalog is held entirely in application memory and the bottleneck is algorithm complexity — but a catalog of 100K products almost certainly lives in a database, making real I/O the critical measurement path.","test_description":"Seed a real test database with 100,000 products spanning realistic category and attribute distributions. Send an HTTP recommendation request for a representative user to the running recommendation service. Measure wall-clock response time from request send to response received. Assert the elapsed time is under 200ms. Run the benchmark at least 5 times and assert the p95 latency is under 200ms.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.76,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"When a recommended product is purchased by the user, the recommendation algorithm deprioritizes it in subsequent requests.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure only appears across two sequential steps: (1) a purchase event updates shared state, and (2) the recommendation algorithm reads that updated state and applies deprioritization logic. A unit test of the ranker alone cannot catch a bug where the purchase event is written to the wrong key, or where the ranker reads the right key but applies the wrong weight. The failure is at the module boundary between purchase recording and recommendation generation. REAL-INFRA: An in-process fake store shared between both modules reproduces the state-propagation failure without needing a real database. LLM-DEP: No. REJECTION-GATE: Would escalate to System only if the purchase event flows through a real message queue that an in-process fake cannot replicate.","test_description":"Wire the purchase-recording module and recommendation module against a shared in-memory store. Call the recommendation pipeline for a user; record the rank of target product P. Record a purchase event for product P. Call the recommendation pipeline again for the same user state. Assert that product P's rank in the second response is strictly lower than its rank in the first response (or that it is absent from the top-N results if the deprioritization is strong enough).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"The recommendation results are deterministic for the same user state — requesting recommendations twice with no intervening user activity returns the same ranked list.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Non-determinism in a pipeline emerges from sources invisible in a single function call: HashMap iteration order, timestamp-based seeding, race conditions in shared caches, or the serendipity module using an unseeded RNG. These only surface when the full pipeline is called twice independently. A unit test of a single pure function cannot catch non-determinism introduced at module boundaries (e.g., the serendipity injector using a different random seed per request). REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed — an in-process pipeline with a fixed-state fake store is sufficient to observe whether two calls return the same output. LLM-DEP: The behavior explicitly asserts determinism; if an LLM were involved, determinism would require temperature=0 and identical seeds, but behavior 10 disqualifies a non-deterministic model as the ranker. REJECTION-GATE: Would lower to Unit only if the entire pipeline is a single pure function; 'two separate requests' implies stateful pipeline execution across multiple modules.","test_description":"Wire the full recommendation pipeline with a fixed user profile and a static in-memory catalog. Call the pipeline twice in sequence with no state changes between calls. Capture the full ranked product-ID list from each call. Assert that the two lists are identical in both content and order, including verifying that any serendipitous items (from behavior 5) appear at the same positions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9867,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9867},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"48272a95-853f-4bab-a8f7-1190d085ffcf","uuid":"687554b1-8f22-479b-a2cc-5d9f929eb98d"}
